The ‘miraculous’ recovery of a surviving student of the Peshawar massacre
A paralytic teenager who had been shot four times in Pakistan's worst terrorist attack succeeded in a "miraculous" recovery after following treatment in the United Kingdom.
Mohamed Ibrahim Khan, 13 years old, the doctors in Pakistan had told him that he would never be able to go.
At least 140 people, most children, were killed when armed men attacked the Peshawar Army public school last December.
Mohamed, who arrived in London last month for the operation, will be discharged later from the hospital.
Just nine months ago, on a regular Tuesday morning, Mohamed was sitting at first aid time and listening carefully to his teachers.
Even then, seven armed men dressed in uniforms of security officers entered public military school.
They wore belts with explosives and had a simple mission to accomplish: to kill all men, women and children in their path.
"I can't forget what happened that day," Mohamed says with a sharp look.
I was sitting in the amphitheater, asking questions... then I heard gunshots out.
The terrorists came in and started killing our professor was burned alive.
Mohamed describes how he pulled four students out of the amphitheater as the carnage unfolded.
Then he says he heard his friend, Hamza, yelling at him.
He said "oh, brother, save me."
I held him by the hand.
Then I was shot in the back, and he in the head.
Most of those killed in the attack were students
Hamza died in Mohamed's arms.
Mohamed remembers that immediately after that he passed out and that the next thing he knew was that he was on a hospital bed, paralyzed from the brass down.
The doctors in Peshawar in northern Pakistan, then the ones in Rawalpindi, near the capital, told his family that there was no treatment and that he would never be able to go.
"When I saw him, I felt my soul coming out," says Sher Khan, Mohamed's father.
Those nine months were the hardest of my life.
But Khan and his wife, Sherbano, refused to believe that their son so passionate about cricket would never be able to use his feet again.
They campaigned and called for help from Pakistani television, attracting support from famous people such as Imran Khan, a cricket player who became a politician.
Eventually, they managed to raise funds to take Mohamed to the United Kingdom and provide treatment at the Harley Street private clinic in London.
The neurosurgeon Irfan Malik described Mohamed as “fearing” when he arrived at the hospital.
"He spent the last [a few] months lying in bed, without being able to move on one side, says Malik.
He was weak, there was a lot of pressure on his back.
He wasn't in a good shape.
A vertebrae at the base of Mohamed's spine had been destroyed
Mohamed had been shot in the shoulder, hip and back during the attack, and his lower spine had been destroyed, leading to paralysis.
However, during a six-hour operation, Malik and his team were able to reseal the nerve endings and rebuild the destroyed part of the column.
Even Malik was surprised by what happened next.
Just a week after the surgery, Mohamed stood up and began to take steps and walk.
We're not expecting such a good result.
It was a miracle," he says.
Within two weeks of the operation, Mohamed is ready to leave the hospital and start the long recovery process.
Mohamed challenged fate and began to go again
He wants to become strong and continue his studies in the United Kingdom.
But he is determined to return to Pakistan, join the army and fight terrorism.
"I feel like I still have a chance to live," he says, showing the weapons images drawn by him next to the school textbooks and pens
Physically, Mohamed gets stronger every day, but psychological trauma he passes through and now is unimaginable.
"My fury has not dropped," he confesses.
In my school, little kids were killed.
What crime did they commit?
His mother wipes out a tear, consoles him on the rise, and says: “I see my son going again.”
He'll be able to keep his life going.
