They cause heart attack and stroke, which are responsible for three quarters of the 3.3 million deaths annually, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory disease.
Research did not include the effects of indoor air pollution, for example from cooking fires, which is estimated to cause an additional 3.4 million deaths per year.
The new study, published in the journal Nature, was the first to highlight various sources of outdoor air pollution and estimated the number of premature deaths caused by these, taking into account road traffic, fossil fuel power plants and other sources.
Researchers have used a detailed computerized model of the global atmosphere to assess the impact of air pollution on different populations, including new information on how pollution affects the inhabitants of China and India.
A third of all premature deaths were the result of the use of fumes, such as wood and coal, for heating homes or cooking, and the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all of which are recognized dangers.
Consumption of this type of internal energy causes half of India's 645 000 annual deaths and one third of China's 1.4 million annual deaths.
However, the research found that the agricultural ammonia emissions had a "remarkable" impact, according to Professor Jos Lelieveld of Germany's Max Planck Chemical Institute, which led the research.
A fifth of the global deaths are caused by these emissions, mainly from cattle, birds and pigs and from the excessive use of fertilizers.
The ammonia reacts with the exhaust gases from traffic and industry and produces tiny particles, being the main reason of the deaths due to pollution of the air from eastern America, Japan and Europe.
"For London, agriculture is the main source," says Leslieveld.
Throughout the United Kingdom, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still an important factor in developed countries, causing one fifth of the deaths, despite measures against polluting vehicles.
This has only caused 5% of deaths globally, but the figure could increase as more and more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
The pollution of air by the plant, especially by coal-operated people, was significant globally, causing one of seven deaths.
In the US it is the main single factor, causing one third of the 55 000 deaths per year, compared with 16% in the United Kingdom.
Natural air pollution, especially in arid regions and with a lot of dust, caused almost a fifth of the global deaths caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some arid countries, being responsible for 92% of the deaths in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
“The overlap between the high pollution level and the large number of residents says their word on public health, but nothing is known about pollution sources responsible for premature deaths,” Jerrett says.
The results are surprising and potentially important for the protection of public health globally.
